font-family="Arial, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, sans-serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats"><fo:block margin-left="0pt"><fo:block font-size="24.8832pt" font-weight="bold"><fo:block keep-with-next.within-column="always" space-before.optimum="10pt" space-before.minimum="10pt * 0.8" space-before.maximum="10pt * 1.2" hyphenate="false" text-align="start" start-indent="0pt" hyphenation-character="-" hyphenation-push-character-count="2" hyphenation-remain-character-count="2">Chapter 7. Resident Sojourners</fo:block></fo:block><fo:block space-before="0.5em" font-style="italic" font-size="14.4pt" font-weight="bold">גרים תושבם - Gerim Toshvim </fo:block></fo:block></fo:block></fo:block>
	
	
	<fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em"><fo:inline font-style="italic">Gerim toshvim</fo:inline> is the plural form of <fo:inline font-style="italic">ger toshav</fo:inline>.
			<fo:inline font-style="italic">Ger toshav</fo:inline>
	</fo:block>
	<fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em">2 Samuel 15:19-21<fo:footnote><fo:inline><fo:inline font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="75%" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" baseline-shift="super">1</fo:inline></fo:inline><fo:footnote-body font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="8pt" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" text-align="justify" start-indent="0pt" end-indent="0pt" text-indent="0pt" hyphenate="true" wrap-option="wrap" linefeed-treatment="treat-as-space">
			<fo:block><fo:inline font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="75%" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" baseline-shift="super">1</fo:inline>"Then said the king to Ittai the Gittite, Wherefore goest thou also with us?
				return to thy place, and abide with the king: for thou art a stranger, and also an
				exile. Whereas thou camest but yesterday, should I this day make thee go up and down
				with us? seeing I go whither I may, return thou, and take back thy brethren: mercy
				and truth be with thee. And Ittai answered the king, and said, As the LORD liveth,
				and as my lord the king liveth, surely in what place my lord the king shall be,
				whether in death or life, even there also will thy servant be. And David said to
				Ittai, Go and pass over. And Ittai the Gittite passed over, and all his men, and all
				the little ones that were with him. And all the country wept with a loud voice, and
				all the people passed over: the king also himself passed over the brook Kidron, and
				all the people passed over, toward the way of the wilderness." - 2 Samuel 15:19-23
				KJV</fo:block>
		</fo:footnote-body></fo:footnote> is talking about the acceptance process of the <fo:inline font-style="italic">nochri</fo:inline> to a
			<fo:inline font-style="italic">ger toshav</fo:inline>. A <fo:inline font-style="italic">ger toshav</fo:inline> is one not only does,
		but accepts the <fo:inline font-style="italic">sheva mitzvot bnei noach</fo:inline>. The
			<fo:inline font-style="italic">Yovel</fo:inline> year does not have to be practiced in order to be a
			<fo:inline font-style="italic">ger toshav</fo:inline>.<fo:footnote><fo:inline><fo:inline font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="75%" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" baseline-shift="super">2</fo:inline></fo:inline><fo:footnote-body font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="8pt" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" text-align="justify" start-indent="0pt" end-indent="0pt" text-indent="0pt" hyphenate="true" wrap-option="wrap" linefeed-treatment="treat-as-space">
			<fo:block><fo:inline font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="75%" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" baseline-shift="super">2</fo:inline>Chofetz Chaim, Mishnah Berurah, 304</fo:block>
			</fo:footnote-body></fo:footnote><fo:footnote><fo:inline><fo:inline font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="75%" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" baseline-shift="super">3</fo:inline></fo:inline><fo:footnote-body font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="8pt" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" text-align="justify" start-indent="0pt" end-indent="0pt" text-indent="0pt" hyphenate="true" wrap-option="wrap" linefeed-treatment="treat-as-space">
				<fo:block><fo:inline font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="75%" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" baseline-shift="super">3</fo:inline>Rabbi Aaron Soloveitchik, Od Yisrael Yoseph Beni Chai, Siymon 3</fo:block>
			</fo:footnote-body></fo:footnote></fo:block>
	<fo:block space-before.minimum="0.5em" space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.maximum="2em" space-after.minimum="0.5em" space-after.optimum="1em" space-after.maximum="2em" keep-together.within-column="always" border-style="solid" border-width="1pt" border-color="black" background-color="#DDDDDD" padding-start="12pt" padding-end="12pt" padding-top="6pt" padding-bottom="6pt" margin-left="0pt" margin-right="0pt" id="d6e730"><fo:block/>
		<fo:block space-before.optimum="0pt" space-before.minimum="0pt" space-before.maximum="0pt"><fo:inline font-weight="bold"><fo:inline font-style="italic">mekablin</fo:inline> of the <fo:inline font-style="italic">ger
					toshav</fo:inline></fo:inline>: <fo:inline font-style="italic">Mekablin</fo:inline> means
				<fo:inline font-style="italic">acceptance</fo:inline>. When someone accepts you into their fraternity,
			into their city walls, or into their country as a citizen, they
				<fo:inline font-style="italic">mekablin</fo:inline> you. You perform an oath to a constitution or some
			creed so that you and the other party are on the same understanding and expectation. The
			word <fo:inline font-style="italic">mekablin</fo:inline> creates a high amount of confusion when it relates to
			non-Jews and <fo:inline font-style="italic">ger toshav</fo:inline> in particular. Many, rabbis included, will
			say the <fo:inline font-style="italic">ger toshav</fo:inline> does not exist today. However, that is not true.
			What the <fo:inline font-style="italic">R"AMBAM</fo:inline> says is that the <fo:inline font-style="italic">ger toshav</fo:inline>
			is not <fo:inline font-style="italic">mekablin</fo:inline> today; not that he doesn't exist. The
				<fo:inline font-style="italic">R"AAVAD</fo:inline> on <fo:inline font-style="italic">Hilchot Issurei Bi'ah 14:7-8</fo:inline>
			explains that the <fo:inline font-style="italic">ger toshav</fo:inline> most certainly does exist today. He is
			just not <fo:inline font-style="italic">mekablin</fo:inline> because the <fo:inline font-style="italic">Yovel</fo:inline> year is
			not in practice.</fo:block>
	</fo:block>
	<fo:block id="d6e749"><fo:block><fo:block><fo:block keep-together.within-column="always" margin-left="0pt" font-family="Arial, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, sans-serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats"><fo:block keep-with-next.within-column="always"><fo:block font-family="Arial, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, sans-serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-weight="bold" keep-with-next.within-column="always" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.optimum="1.0em" space-before.maximum="1.2em" text-align="start" start-indent="0pt"><fo:marker marker-class-name="section.head.marker">History</fo:marker><fo:block font-size="20.735999999999997pt">History</fo:block></fo:block></fo:block></fo:block></fo:block></fo:block>
		
		<fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em">This History of the <fo:inline font-style="italic">ger toshav</fo:inline>.</fo:block>
		<fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em">The Latin <fo:inline font-style="italic">proselyte</fo:inline> literally means <fo:inline font-style="italic">resident
				sojourner</fo:inline></fo:block>
		<fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em">Cite from the Rogetchover Gaon</fo:block>
		<fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em">Midrash haGadol (yemenite Tradition) is the source for much of Rambam's Mishneh
			Torah.</fo:block>
	</fo:block>
	<fo:block id="d6e758"><fo:block><fo:block><fo:block keep-together.within-column="always" margin-left="0pt" font-family="Arial, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, sans-serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats"><fo:block keep-with-next.within-column="always"><fo:block font-family="Arial, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, sans-serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-weight="bold" keep-with-next.within-column="always" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.optimum="1.0em" space-before.maximum="1.2em" text-align="start" start-indent="0pt"><fo:marker marker-class-name="section.head.marker">Halacha</fo:marker><fo:block font-size="20.735999999999997pt">Halacha</fo:block></fo:block></fo:block></fo:block></fo:block></fo:block>
		
		<fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em">Halachah for the <fo:inline font-style="italic">ger toshav</fo:inline></fo:block>
		<fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em"><fo:inline font-style="italic">Ger toshav</fo:inline> may flee to a city of refuge. R"ITVA on Makkos
			9a</fo:block>
		<fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em">There might be a contradiction between the Raavad's definition of a <fo:inline font-style="italic">ger
				toshav</fo:inline> and the <fo:inline font-style="italic">ger within your gates</fo:inline>. The reason is
			the the Raavad <fo:inline font-style="italic">ger toshav</fo:inline> is not allowed to dwell within the
			city(Raavad on Issurei Biah 14:7), but Devarim says that the <fo:inline font-style="italic">ger
				toshav</fo:inline>
			<fo:inline font-weight="bold">is</fo:inline> within the gates: "Ye shall not eat of any thing
			that dieth of itself: thou shalt give it unto the stranger that is in thy gates, that he
			may eat it; or thou mayest sell it unto an alien: for thou art an holy people unto the
			LORD thy God. Thou shalt not seethe a kid in his mother's milk." - Deu 14:21 KJV</fo:block>
		<fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em">There is also another contradiction between this <fo:inline font-style="italic">ger toshav</fo:inline> and
			the <fo:inline font-style="italic">ger within your gates</fo:inline> from I think the Talmud, where the Talmud
			says the ger within your gates is a <fo:inline font-style="italic">ger tzedek</fo:inline>.</fo:block>
		<fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em"><fo:inline font-style="italic">Na'aman</fo:inline> was a <fo:inline font-style="italic">ger toshav</fo:inline> (Gittin
			57b).</fo:block>
		<fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em">The "God fearer" of <fo:inline font-style="italic">Tehillim</fo:inline> 115:11 is a <fo:inline font-style="italic">ger
				toshav</fo:inline> per <fo:inline font-style="italic">Rashi</fo:inline> commentary.</fo:block>
	</fo:block>
	<fo:block id="d6e781"><fo:block><fo:block><fo:block keep-together.within-column="always" margin-left="0pt" font-family="Arial, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, sans-serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats"><fo:block keep-with-next.within-column="always"><fo:block font-family="Arial, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, sans-serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-weight="bold" keep-with-next.within-column="always" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.optimum="1.0em" space-before.maximum="1.2em" text-align="start" start-indent="0pt"><fo:marker marker-class-name="section.head.marker">Responsa</fo:marker><fo:block font-size="20.735999999999997pt">Responsa</fo:block></fo:block></fo:block></fo:block></fo:block></fo:block>
		
		<fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em"><fo:inline font-weight="bold">Statement:</fo:inline> The Ger Toshav doesn't exist today</fo:block>
		<fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em"><fo:inline font-weight="bold">Response:</fo:inline> Raavad on Hilchot Issurei Bi'ah
			14:7-8</fo:block>
		<fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em"><fo:inline font-weight="bold">Statement:</fo:inline> A <fo:inline font-style="italic">ger toshav</fo:inline> is still
			a <fo:inline font-style="italic">goy</fo:inline></fo:block>
		<fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em"><fo:inline font-weight="bold">Response:</fo:inline> Hilchot Maachalot Assurot 11:8:"when we say
			plainly 'goy', we mean an idolator".</fo:block>
		<fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em">Concerning the Issurei Biah 14:7:You say that the ger toshav is a goy even after he
			swears off idolatry.Using that logic, when Issurei Biah 13:3 says a ger tzedek is a goy
			as well, you're still able to call him a goy:"When a goy desires to enter into the
			covenant..."However, a ger tzedek is no longer a goy, lest you say all converts cannot
			keep shabbat, study Torah, etc. per Hilchot Melachim 10:9 "A goy cannot study Torah...".
			Following the rule in set theory, a subset follows all the attributes of its superset,
			so when you call a ger a subset of goy, this cannot be the case.</fo:block>
		<fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em">For instance:set all integers: {1,2,3,4,5,6,..}set even integers: {2,4,6,...}Set "even
			integers" being a subset of "all integers", and if "all integers" turn pink then "even
			integers" would turn pink due to inheritance by set theory. Therefore, ger toshav is not
			a subset of goy. Rather, a ger toshav(a non-idolator) is no longer a goy(idolator). They
			are not goy(idolator). They are ger(non-idolator).The only way(and I would agree with
			you) that gerim are subsets, is in the Torah definition of goy, such as bnei Yisrael
			being a goy kodesh(a holy nation). However, we're not talking in the written Torah term,
			but rather in the halachic term, as defined by the Rambam, Hilchot Maachalot Assurot
			11:8:"when we say plainly 'goy', we mean an idolator". Hilchot Maachalot Assurot 11:8 is
			true statement. If it is true, the you should read Issurei Biah 14:7 as:"Who is a ger
			toshav? This is an idolator which accepts upon himself to not serve idolatry, [along]
			with the other commandments commanded to the children of Noach"This also explains why
			rabbis refer to ger toshav as "half-converts"(as in Avodah Berurah, Avodah Zarah 64b).
			They were once idol-worshippers, who accepted not to be.You have not shown my argument
			to be invalid or false. Standing alone and apart from the rest of Mishneh Torah, your
			argument for Issurei Biah is valid(which would assume the Torah definition of goy), but
			coupled with the axiom of Maachalot Assurot 11:8(which assumes the halachic Rambam
			definition of goy), your argument is not valid.</fo:block>
	</fo:block>
</fo:flow></fo:page-sequence>
