olor="black"><fo:table-column column-number="1" column-width="proportional-column-width(1)"/><fo:table-column column-number="2" column-width="proportional-column-width(1)"/><fo:table-column column-number="3" column-width="proportional-column-width(1)"/><fo:table-body><fo:table-row block-progression-dimension.minimum="14pt"><fo:table-cell text-align="start" display-align="after" relative-align="baseline"><fo:block><fo:block/></fo:block></fo:table-cell><fo:table-cell text-align="center" display-align="after" relative-align="baseline"><fo:block><fo:block><fo:page-number/></fo:block></fo:block></fo:table-cell><fo:table-cell text-align="end" display-align="after" relative-align="baseline"><fo:block><fo:block/></fo:block></fo:table-cell></fo:table-row></fo:table-body></fo:table></fo:block></fo:static-content><fo:static-content flow-name="xsl-region-after-blank"><fo:block font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" margin-left="0pt"><fo:table table-layout="fixed" width="100%" border-top-width="0.5pt" border-top-style="solid" border-top-color="black"><fo:table-column column-number="1" column-width="proportional-column-width(1)"/><fo:table-column column-number="2" column-width="proportional-column-width(1)"/><fo:table-column column-number="3" column-width="proportional-column-width(1)"/><fo:table-body><fo:table-row block-progression-dimension.minimum="14pt"><fo:table-cell text-align="start" display-align="after" relative-align="baseline"><fo:block><fo:block/></fo:block></fo:table-cell><fo:table-cell text-align="center" display-align="after" relative-align="baseline"><fo:block><fo:block><fo:page-number/></fo:block></fo:block></fo:table-cell><fo:table-cell text-align="end" display-align="after" relative-align="baseline"><fo:block><fo:block/></fo:block></fo:table-cell></fo:table-row></fo:table-body></fo:table></fo:block></fo:static-content><fo:flow flow-name="xsl-region-body" start-indent="4pc" end-indent="0pt"><fo:block id="ger_tzedek"><fo:block font-family="Arial, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, sans-serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats"><fo:block margin-left="0pt"><fo:block font-size="24.8832pt" font-weight="bold"><fo:block keep-with-next.within-column="always" space-before.optimum="10pt" space-before.minimum="10pt * 0.8" space-before.maximum="10pt * 1.2" hyphenate="false" text-align="start" start-indent="0pt" hyphenation-character="-" hyphenation-push-character-count="2" hyphenation-remain-character-count="2">Chapter 8. Sojourners of Righteousness</fo:block></fo:block><fo:block space-before="0.5em" font-style="italic" font-size="14.4pt" font-weight="bold">גרי צדק - Gerei Tzedek</fo:block></fo:block></fo:block></fo:block>
	
	
	<fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em">Rambam, Book of Mitzvot, 3rd Principle(p.17 Touger), all bones of the human body yearn to
		keep the mitzvot. All human beings have 613 parts of the body(Tanya, Ari Kaplan Inner Space,
		Transforming the Inner Self, pg 38, ft 52, Likutei Torah, Ekev 13b; 14a). These 613 parts
		correlate to the mitzvot and their respective conduits that connect to
		<fo:inline font-style="italic">haShem</fo:inline>.<fo:footnote><fo:inline><fo:inline font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="75%" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" baseline-shift="super">1</fo:inline></fo:inline><fo:footnote-body font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="8pt" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" text-align="justify" start-indent="0pt" end-indent="0pt" text-indent="0pt" hyphenate="true" wrap-option="wrap" linefeed-treatment="treat-as-space"><fo:block><fo:inline font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="75%" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" baseline-shift="super">1</fo:inline>Tanya, Iggeret haKodesh, 7</fo:block></fo:footnote-body></fo:footnote></fo:block>
	<fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em">Rambam, Book of Mitzvot, Mitvah 3, all men are called to love haShem.</fo:block>
	<fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em">This is probably the hardest of the <fo:inline font-style="italic">gerim</fo:inline> to translate. The reason is
		that the Hebrew word <fo:inline font-style="italic">tzedek</fo:inline> doesn't have a word to translate to that
		encompasses its properties of truth, correctness, uprightness, and righteousness.</fo:block>
	<fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em"><fo:inline font-style="italic">Sojourners of Righteousness</fo:inline> are seekers of Torah in whatever form
		they find it. They strive to constantly know <fo:inline font-style="italic">haShem</fo:inline> better and clearer.
		They are always increasing and never decreasing in this pursuit. If they fail, they
		spiritually fall to the status of <fo:inline font-style="italic">ger toshav</fo:inline>: the ger that is resting
		in place.</fo:block>
	<fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em">The <fo:inline font-style="italic">ger tzedek</fo:inline> is the ultimate path that <fo:inline font-style="italic">haShem</fo:inline>
		desires for <fo:inline font-style="italic">bnei Noach</fo:inline>(Rambam, Book of Mitzvot, Mitzvah 3). The
			<fo:inline font-style="italic">ger tzedek</fo:inline> may have been from the lowly source/status of a
			<fo:inline font-style="italic">goy</fo:inline>, but is now seeking the ultimate Source of his true existence:
			<fo:inline font-style="italic">haShem</fo:inline>. However, <fo:inline font-style="italic">haShem</fo:inline> does not require a
			<fo:inline font-style="italic">goy</fo:inline> to become a <fo:inline font-style="italic">ger tzedek</fo:inline>.
			<fo:inline font-style="italic">haShem</fo:inline> only requires that he keep the <fo:inline font-style="italic">sheva mitzvot bnei
			Noach</fo:inline>. The passive nature of the <fo:inline font-style="italic">sheva mitzvot bnei
			Noach</fo:inline> allows the <fo:inline font-style="italic">goy</fo:inline>(if he keeps the <fo:inline font-style="italic">sheva
			mitzvot bnei Noach</fo:inline> he is now a plain <fo:inline font-style="italic">ben Noach</fo:inline>) to do as
		he pleases so long as he does not transgress the seven. It appears to me that these are
		designed in such a way to restrict any damage to creation if the <fo:inline font-style="italic">ben
			Noach</fo:inline> does not desire to seek his Source: <fo:inline font-style="italic">haShem</fo:inline>.
		However, the stringincy of the laws most likely will incentivise the <fo:inline font-style="italic">ben
			Noach</fo:inline> to seek the Source of the harsh judgements of the seven, should he
		transgress them. The initiation by <fo:inline font-style="italic">haShem Elokim</fo:inline> to give the harsh laws
		for <fo:inline font-style="italic">bnei Noach</fo:inline> is so that <fo:inline font-style="italic">bnei Noach</fo:inline> will be
		encouraged to seek the Source of the harsh judgements. This initiation by <fo:inline font-style="italic">haShem
			Elokim</fo:inline> is given through the teaching of His <fo:inline font-style="italic">Torah</fo:inline>, by
		the elders of his community, etc. This is called illah eltatah(the higher initiation). "Why
		does <fo:inline font-style="italic">Elokim</fo:inline> act so harshly toward me if I trangress? If I even steal a
			<fo:inline font-style="italic">pruta's</fo:inline> worth of someone else's, I am worthy of decapitation!" When
		the <fo:inline font-style="italic">ben Noach</fo:inline> starts to earnestly question why these judgements are so
		harsh and starts to seek their Source, the judgements are now sweatened, because he is now
		seeking the Wisdom of <fo:inline font-style="italic">haShem</fo:inline>. This is called illah teta'ah(the lower
		initiation). This is the beginning of the path of the <fo:inline font-style="italic">ger tzedek</fo:inline>. The
		fear of <fo:inline font-style="italic">haShem</fo:inline> is the beginning of Wisdom. This wisdom leads to the
			<fo:inline font-style="italic">da'at</fo:inline>. <fo:inline font-style="italic">Da'at</fo:inline> leads to a love of
			<fo:inline font-style="italic">haShem</fo:inline>. The love of <fo:inline font-style="italic">haShem</fo:inline> leads to doing
		positive commandments. The purpose of Wisdom is teshuvah and good deeds.<fo:footnote><fo:inline><fo:inline font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="75%" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" baseline-shift="super">2</fo:inline></fo:inline><fo:footnote-body font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="8pt" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" text-align="justify" start-indent="0pt" end-indent="0pt" text-indent="0pt" hyphenate="true" wrap-option="wrap" linefeed-treatment="treat-as-space">
			<fo:block><fo:inline font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="75%" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" baseline-shift="super">2</fo:inline> Brachos 17a</fo:block>
		</fo:footnote-body></fo:footnote></fo:block>
	<fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em">The <fo:inline font-style="italic">ger tzedek</fo:inline> may spiritually occilate out of this seeking and
		yearning and fall to a lesser status such as a <fo:inline font-style="italic">ger toshav</fo:inline> or
			<fo:inline font-style="italic">goy</fo:inline>. If the <fo:inline font-style="italic">ger tzedek</fo:inline> has been
			<fo:inline font-style="italic">mekablin</fo:inline> to <fo:inline font-style="italic">Israel</fo:inline>, then there are
		consequences to that as well, that <fo:inline font-style="italic">Israel</fo:inline> has a
			<fo:inline font-style="italic">mitvah</fo:inline> to act on.</fo:block>
	<fo:block space-before.minimum="0.5em" space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.maximum="2em" space-after.minimum="0.5em" space-after.optimum="1em" space-after.maximum="2em" keep-together.within-column="always" border-style="solid" border-width="1pt" border-color="black" background-color="#DDDDDD" padding-start="12pt" padding-end="12pt" padding-top="6pt" padding-bottom="6pt" margin-left="0pt" margin-right="0pt" id="d6e855"><fo:block/>
		<fo:block space-before.optimum="0pt" space-before.minimum="0pt" space-before.maximum="0pt"><fo:inline font-weight="bold">Note:</fo:inline>
			<fo:inline font-style="italic">Gerei Tzedek</fo:inline> is often translated as <fo:inline font-style="italic">converts</fo:inline>,
				<fo:inline font-style="italic">proselytes</fo:inline>, or <fo:inline font-style="italic">righteous strangers</fo:inline>.
			Actually, <fo:inline font-style="italic">gerei tzedek</fo:inline> is a Hebrew construct and should be
			translated as <fo:inline font-style="italic">sojourners <fo:inline font-weight="bold">of</fo:inline>
				righteousness</fo:inline>. It is hard to translate <fo:inline font-style="italic">tzedek</fo:inline> into
			English and "righteousness" is probably the closest thing. In my opinion, a more proper
			definition of <fo:inline font-style="italic">tzedek</fo:inline> would be something like "proper path" or
			"proper way".</fo:block>
		<fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em">This, more proper translation, lends <fo:inline font-style="italic">gerei tzedek</fo:inline> to be
			sojourners who are in a process of walking a proper path and not necessarily already at
			the destination of the path. Such a <fo:inline font-style="italic">ger</fo:inline> is a <fo:inline font-style="italic">ger
				gamor</fo:inline>, or <fo:inline font-style="italic">complete ger</fo:inline> and one who begins to settle.
				<fo:inline font-style="italic">Gerim</fo:inline> are known to live in tents and not permanent dwellings.
			It appears to me, that such a person is an individual that comes before a <fo:inline font-style="italic">beit
				din</fo:inline> to be accepted as a <fo:inline font-style="italic">ger tzedek</fo:inline> proper.</fo:block>
	</fo:block>
	<fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em">We can deduce that a <fo:inline font-style="italic">ger tzedek</fo:inline> exists outside of acceptance of a
			<fo:inline font-style="italic">beit din</fo:inline> because someone who does <fo:inline font-style="italic">teshuvah</fo:inline> is
		a <fo:inline font-style="italic">tzaddik</fo:inline> at that moment. Also, any <fo:inline font-style="italic">ger</fo:inline> who is
		truly seeking haShem, Torah, or attaching to his people for the sake of Heaven is a
			<fo:inline font-style="italic">ger tzedek</fo:inline>. This type <fo:inline font-style="italic">ger tzedek</fo:inline> is one
		inwardly and is subjective. There is another <fo:inline font-style="italic">ger tzedek</fo:inline>, a
			<fo:inline font-style="italic">ger gamor</fo:inline> or completed <fo:inline font-style="italic">ger</fo:inline>, that objectively
		goes before a <fo:inline font-style="italic">beit din</fo:inline> to be tried and accepted as a <fo:inline font-style="italic">ger
			tzedek</fo:inline>. This is a newly defined type of definition for the <fo:inline font-style="italic">ger
			tzedek</fo:inline></fo:block>
	<fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em">Going before a <fo:inline font-style="italic">beit din</fo:inline> and asking to be accepted as a <fo:inline font-style="italic">ger
			tzedek</fo:inline> is required by halacha to become part of <fo:inline font-style="italic">klal
			Yisrael</fo:inline>. Before this acceptance by a <fo:inline font-style="italic">beit din</fo:inline>, the
			<fo:inline font-style="italic">ger tzedek</fo:inline> cannot and should not expect others to accept him as a
			<fo:inline font-style="italic">ger tzedek</fo:inline>, particularly in a Jewish community. Some reasons for
		this, is because <fo:inline font-style="italic">klal Yisrael</fo:inline> has certain halachic obligations to the
			<fo:inline font-style="italic">ger</fo:inline> and at this time when there is no practicing
			<fo:inline font-style="italic">Yovel</fo:inline>, only the <fo:inline font-style="italic">ger tzedek</fo:inline> can be accepted and
		have those obligations met. It is a <fo:inline font-style="italic">mitzvah</fo:inline> for <fo:inline font-style="italic">klal
			Yisrael</fo:inline> to love the <fo:inline font-style="italic">ger</fo:inline> and not taunt him. The
			<fo:inline font-style="italic">ger</fo:inline> should also love <fo:inline font-style="italic">bnei Yisrael</fo:inline> and not
		expect them to open their gates of the community to just anyone who comes off the street.
		That would be dangerous and unloving. Therefore, one should not refer to themselves as a
			<fo:inline font-style="italic">ger tzedek</fo:inline> unless confirmed as such.</fo:block>
	<fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em">"Every year a Jew must reach a level of renewal and "geirus" similar to that of a newborn
		baby. This is the whole idea behind the seven weeks of counting the omer, a time for
		purifying oneself of impurities in order to reach a level of "geirus"." - Nesivos Sholom,
		Shavuos - Ma'amar Echad, B'Yom haBikkurim B'Hikrivchem Mincha Chadasha L'haShem, sup Bnei
		Avraham Ahuvecha: Gerim in Chassidic Thought. A ger( tzedek or toshav) is like a newborn
		baby: read Avodah Berurah, Avodah Zara 64b. The ger and the ben Yisrael has the same
		spiritual state. Both animal souls are emanating from klipat nogah and refining until a
		Godly soul is welcomed, which is Shavuot.</fo:block>
	<fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em">All that <fo:inline font-style="italic">Yaacov</fo:inline> learned from <fo:inline font-style="italic">Shem</fo:inline> and
			<fo:inline font-style="italic">Ever</fo:inline> he gave to <fo:inline font-style="italic">Yoseph</fo:inline> (Rashi, B'Reisheet
		37:3-5).</fo:block>
	<fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em"/>
	<fo:block id="d6e913"><fo:block><fo:block><fo:block keep-together.within-column="always" margin-left="0pt" font-family="Arial, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, sans-serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats"><fo:block keep-with-next.within-column="always"><fo:block font-family="Arial, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, sans-serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-weight="bold" keep-with-next.within-column="always" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.optimum="1.0em" space-before.maximum="1.2em" text-align="start" start-indent="0pt"><fo:marker marker-class-name="section.head.marker">History</fo:marker><fo:block font-size="20.735999999999997pt">History</fo:block></fo:block></fo:block></fo:block></fo:block></fo:block>
		
		<fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em">This History of the <fo:inline font-style="italic">ger tzedek</fo:inline></fo:block>
	</fo:block>
	<fo:block id="d6e917"><fo:block><fo:block><fo:block keep-together.within-column="always" margin-left="0pt" font-family="Arial, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, sans-serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats"><fo:block keep-with-next.within-column="always"><fo:block font-family="Arial, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, sans-serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-weight="bold" keep-with-next.within-column="always" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.optimum="1.0em" space-before.maximum="1.2em" text-align="start" start-indent="0pt"><fo:marker marker-class-name="section.head.marker">Halacha</fo:marker><fo:block font-size="20.735999999999997pt">Halacha</fo:block></fo:block></fo:block></fo:block></fo:block></fo:block>
		
		<fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em">Halachah for the <fo:inline font-style="italic">ger tzedek</fo:inline>. Hilchot Issurei Bi'ah 13:4</fo:block>
	</fo:block>
	<fo:block id="d6e921"><fo:block><fo:block><fo:block keep-together.within-column="always" margin-left="0pt" font-family="Arial, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, sans-serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats"><fo:block keep-with-next.within-column="always"><fo:block font-family="Arial, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, sans-serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-weight="bold" keep-with-next.within-column="always" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.optimum="1.0em" space-before.maximum="1.2em" text-align="start" start-indent="0pt"><fo:marker marker-class-name="section.head.marker">Responsa</fo:marker><fo:block font-size="20.735999999999997pt">Responsa</fo:block></fo:block></fo:block></fo:block></fo:block></fo:block>
		
		<fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em"><fo:inline font-weight="bold">Statement:</fo:inline> The <fo:inline font-style="italic">ger tzedek</fo:inline> must
			be mekablin</fo:block>
		<fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em"><fo:inline font-weight="bold">Response:</fo:inline> The <fo:inline font-style="italic">ger tzedek</fo:inline> exists
			even outside of <fo:inline font-style="italic">mekablin</fo:inline> to a <fo:inline font-style="italic">beit din</fo:inline>. It's
			just that the <fo:inline font-style="italic">ger tzedek</fo:inline> is not revealed that he is a <fo:inline font-style="italic">ger
				tzedek</fo:inline> until he is <fo:inline font-style="italic">mekablin</fo:inline>. He cannot go around
			telling <fo:inline font-style="italic">klal Yisrael</fo:inline> that he is a <fo:inline font-style="italic">ger tzedek</fo:inline>
			and expect <fo:inline font-style="italic">klal Yisrael</fo:inline> to interact with him as such until he is
				<fo:inline font-style="italic">mekablin</fo:inline> by a <fo:inline font-style="italic">beit din</fo:inline>.</fo:block>
	</fo:block>
</fo:flow></fo:page-sequence>
